data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which work identically in .NET 8. No migration is needed for thread-abort concerns.

**However**, the code has a classic **closure-over-loop-variable** bug and would benefit from modernization:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item =>
        {
            item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
        });
    }
}
```

**Why `Parallel.ForEach`?**
- Eliminates manual thread management
- Uses the thread pool efficiently
- Fixes the captured-variable bug (each iteration gets its own `item`)
- If you later need cancellation, pass a `ParallelOptions` with a `CancellationToken` — the modern replacement for `Thread.Abort`
